<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n52150d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n52" href="#n52150d">N52 (VI.B.42)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n52all.htm#n52150d"> 150(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> pied horse <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n52150d"> <li>FW unlocated</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">&ldquo;Ay, Sir,&rdquo; said Blue-Chin <font color="green">[Zekiel Irons]</font>: I never forget a face.&rdquo; &ldquo;Par nobile,&rdquo; sneered the angler <font color="green">[Dangerfield]</font> quietly.. &ldquo;In the year &apos;45, eh&mdash;go on.&rdquo; &ldquo;Ay, Sir; he <font color="green">[Sturk]</font> slept in the &lsquo;<mark>Pied Horse</mark>&rsquo;, at Newmarket, and was in all the fun. Next day he broke his arm badly, and slept there in the closet off Mr. Beauclerc&apos;s room that night under laudanum, and remained ten days longer in the house. Mr. Beauclerc&apos;s chamber was the &lsquo;fleur de luce&rsquo;. Barnabus Sturk, Esq. When I saw him here <font color="green">[in Chapelizod]</font>, half the length of the street away, I knew him and his name on the instant. I never forget things.&rdquo; <small> J. Sheridan Le Fanu, <a name="HBC2" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#HBC2"><cite title="source">The House by the Churchyard</cite></a> (1899) 131 (Some Old Recollections)</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
